Looking at this proof goal, I need to show that the function `fun i ω => i ∈ X ω` is independent under the probability measure `P`, given that `X` follows a Bernoulli distribution on `u` with parameter `p`.

The key insight is that `IsBernoulliOn X u p P` means `HasLaw X Ber(u, p) P`, which means the distribution of `X` under `P` equals `Ber(u, p)`. The Bernoulli distribution `Ber(u, p)` is defined as a product measure (via `infinitePi`), which inherently encodes independence.

I need to use the fact that if `X` has the law of a product measure, then the coordinate projections are independent. The composition `fun i ω => i ∈ X ω` can be viewed as the coordinate projection at `i` of the measure on `ι → Bool` (viewing membership as a Boolean function).

```lean
lemma IsBernoulliOn.iIndepFun_mem (hX : IsBernoulliOn X u p P) :
    iIndepFun (fun i ω ↦ i ∈ X ω) P := by
  rw [← hX.map_eq]
  exact iIndepFun.comp (iIndepFun_infinitePi _) (fun _ => measurable_pi_apply _) fun _ => by fun_prop
```
